Lastly, Article 3(3) of the GDPR mentions the application of the GDPR as imposed by #internationalaw, but at this point I cannot see how can international law get involved in the metaverse, unless we consider it as a separate foreign jurisdiction (farfetched, right?)
The human person controlling the avatar? The first option is clear for me, at least at this stage, as avatars cannot be data holders because they are not natural persons. However, some argue that avatars should be granted #legalpersonality (https://doi.org/10.1365/s43439-022-00056-9…)...
The GDPR will also apply when data subjects are in the EU/EEA, disregarding the data controller’s location, whenever there is an offer of goods and services, or behaviour monitoring (Article 3(2) GDPR). Who is the #DataSubject here? The avatar (not located in any physical space)?
Other #Avatars interacting with you? The criteria to establish the data controller is the power to determine the purposes and means for the processing of #personaldata (Article 4(7) GDPR), thus the identification of the controller might depend on the specific case.
Article 3 of the #GDPR sets up its territorial scope. But... when does the GDPR apply to the #metaverse?
For a start, when the #datacontroller is located in the EU/EEA and it processes personal data through that establishment (Article 3(1) GDPR). Who is the data controller here?

Lastly, Article 3(3) of the GDPR mentions the application of the GDPR as imposed by #internationalaw, but at this point I cannot see how can international law get involved in the metaverse, unless we consider it as a separate foreign jurisdiction (farfetched, right?)
The human person controlling the avatar? The first option is clear for me, at least at this stage, as avatars cannot be data holders because they are not natural persons. However, some argue that avatars should be granted #legalpersonality (https://doi.org/10.1365/s43439-022-00056-9…)...
The GDPR will also apply when data subjects are in the EU/EEA, disregarding the data controller’s location, whenever there is an offer of goods and services, or behaviour monitoring (Article 3(2) GDPR). Who is the #DataSubject here? The avatar (not located in any physical space)?
Other #Avatars interacting with you? The criteria to establish the data controller is the power to determine the purposes and means for the processing of #personaldata (Article 4(7) GDPR), thus the identification of the controller might depend on the specific case.
Article 3 of the #GDPR sets up its territorial scope. But... when does the GDPR apply to the #metaverse?
For a start, when the #datacontroller is located in the EU/EEA and it processes personal data through that establishment (Article 3(1) GDPR). Who is the data controller here?

Lastly, Article 3(3) of the GDPR mentions the application of the GDPR as imposed by #internationalaw, but at this point I cannot see how can international law get involved in the metaverse, unless we consider it as a separate foreign jurisdiction (farfetched, right?)
The human person controlling the avatar? The first option is clear for me, at least at this stage, as avatars cannot be data holders because they are not natural persons. However, some argue that avatars should be granted #legalpersonality (https://doi.org/10.1365/s43439-022-00056-9…)...
The GDPR will also apply when data subjects are in the EU/EEA, disregarding the data controller’s location, whenever there is an offer of goods and services, or behaviour monitoring (Article 3(2) GDPR). Who is the #DataSubject here? The avatar (not located in any physical space)?
Other #Avatars interacting with you? The criteria to establish the data controller is the power to determine the purposes and means for the processing of #personaldata (Article 4(7) GDPR), thus the identification of the controller might depend on the specific case.
Article 3 of the #GDPR sets up its territorial scope. But... when does the GDPR apply to the #metaverse?
For a start, when the #datacontroller is located in the EU/EEA and it processes personal data through that establishment (Article 3(1) GDPR). Who is the data controller here?

Lastly, Article 3(3) of the GDPR mentions the application of the GDPR as imposed by #internationalaw, but at this point I cannot see how can international law get involved in the metaverse, unless we consider it as a separate foreign jurisdiction (farfetched, right?)
The human person controlling the avatar? The first option is clear for me, at least at this stage, as avatars cannot be data holders because they are not natural persons. However, some argue that avatars should be granted #legalpersonality (https://doi.org/10.1365/s43439-022-00056-9…)...
The GDPR will also apply when data subjects are in the EU/EEA, disregarding the data controller’s location, whenever there is an offer of goods and services, or behaviour monitoring (Article 3(2) GDPR). Who is the #DataSubject here? The avatar (not located in any physical space)?
Other #Avatars interacting with you? The criteria to establish the data controller is the power to determine the purposes and means for the processing of #personaldata (Article 4(7) GDPR), thus the identification of the controller might depend on the specific case.
Article 3 of the #GDPR sets up its territorial scope. But... when does the GDPR apply to the #metaverse?
For a start, when the #datacontroller is located in the EU/EEA and it processes personal data through that establishment (Article 3(1) GDPR). Who is the data controller here?

Lastly, Article 3(3) of the GDPR mentions the application of the GDPR as imposed by #internationalaw, but at this point I cannot see how can international law get involved in the metaverse, unless we consider it as a separate foreign jurisdiction (farfetched, right?)
The human person controlling the avatar? The first option is clear for me, at least at this stage, as avatars cannot be data holders because they are not natural persons. However, some argue that avatars should be granted #legalpersonality (https://doi.org/10.1365/s43439-022-00056-9…)...
The GDPR will also apply when data subjects are in the EU/EEA, disregarding the data controller’s location, whenever there is an offer of goods and services, or behaviour monitoring (Article 3(2) GDPR). Who is the #DataSubject here? The avatar (not located in any physical space)?
Other #Avatars interacting with you? The criteria to establish the data controller is the power to determine the purposes and means for the processing of #personaldata (Article 4(7) GDPR), thus the identification of the controller might depend on the specific case.
Article 3 of the #GDPR sets up its territorial scope. But... when does the GDPR apply to the #metaverse?
For a start, when the #datacontroller is located in the EU/EEA and it processes personal data through that establishment (Article 3(1) GDPR). Who is the data controller here?
